00:08:31.960 --> 00:08:39.210
We’ve talked about solar panels and nuclear
batteries, but did you know there are more

00:08:39.210 --> 00:08:44.060
than 30 spacecraft were launched with nuclear
fission reactors?

00:08:44.060 --> 00:08:48.920
One from the US, and the rest from the Soviet
Union.

00:08:48.920 --> 00:08:52.970
Space-based nuclear fission reactors are similar
to the kinds of reactors used down here on

00:08:52.970 --> 00:08:54.930
the surface to supply electricity.

00:08:54.930 --> 00:09:01.160
They use uranium-235 as a fuel for a fission
reaction, where the nucleus is split, releasing

00:09:01.160 --> 00:09:02.160
energy.

00:09:02.160 --> 00:09:08.390
A kilogram of uranium can provide as much
energy as 3 million kilograms of burning coal.

00:09:08.390 --> 00:09:15.000
The United States launched their SNAP-10A
spacecraft in 1965, and it operated for 43

00:09:15.000 --> 00:09:17.080
days before it stopped functioning.

00:09:17.080 --> 00:09:23.310
It’s now in a slowly deteriorating orbit
that’ll take another 3,000 years or so before

00:09:23.310 --> 00:09:24.770
it crashes back to Earth.

00:09:24.770 --> 00:09:30.060
Don’t worry, its nuclear material should
be largely decayed by then.

00:09:30.060 --> 00:09:35.170
During the space race, the Soviets equipped
31 of their RORSAT reconnaissance satellites

00:09:35.170 --> 00:09:37.710
with BES-5 fission reactors.

00:09:37.710 --> 00:09:41.730
These could generate 3,000 watts of usable
electricity.

00:09:41.730 --> 00:09:47.980
They also equipped two TOPAZ satellites that
could produce 5,000 watts of electricity.

00:09:47.980 --> 00:09:49.890
The Soviets had a few mishaps, though.

00:09:49.890 --> 00:09:58.170
In 1977, they launched their Kosmos 954 spy
satellite which had a BES-5 fission reactor

00:09:58.170 --> 00:10:01.980
with 50 kg of uranium-235 on board.

00:10:01.980 --> 00:10:05.750
The spacecraft suffered a series of malfunctions
and they lost control of it.

00:10:05.750 --> 00:10:10.090
Soviet officials assured the world that the
spacecraft would burn up in the atmosphere

00:10:10.090 --> 00:10:14.830
or hold together when it crashed into the
ground.

00:10:14.830 --> 00:10:19.230
Because it had been launched into an extreme
65-degree orbital inclination, it had the

00:10:19.230 --> 00:10:23.740
potential to crash into almost any population
center across the world.

00:10:23.740 --> 00:10:29.280
When it came down, in 1977, the reactor came
apart almost immediately as it struck the

00:10:29.280 --> 00:10:32.810
atmosphere, coating itself in radioactive
material.

00:10:32.810 --> 00:10:38.370
Then it broke up into large chunks which fell
to Earth over a 600-kilometer track in Canada’s

00:10:38.370 --> 00:10:41.280
Northwest Territories.

00:10:41.280 --> 00:10:48.680
Canada was only able to find, clean up and
dispose of about 1% of the radioactive spacecraft

00:10:48.680 --> 00:10:51.810
chunks, the rest is still out there.

00:10:51.810 --> 00:10:56.770
Fortunately none of the other fission reactors
are expected to return to Earth anytime soon.

00:10:56.770 --> 00:11:02.310
Like SNAP-10A, they’ll take hundreds or
thousands of years to re-enter the atmosphere.

00:11:02.310 --> 00:11:06.950
Considering the dangers, no space agencies
have launched spacecraft with fission reactors

00:11:06.950 --> 00:11:12.310
in over 30 years, but it looks like the technology
might return again soon.

00:11:12.310 --> 00:11:16.810
NASA recently announced that they’re working
on a new space-based fission reactor technology

00:11:16.810 --> 00:11:18.180
called Kilopower.

00:11:18.180 --> 00:11:23.470
They held a press conference in May, 2018
announcing that they’d completed their ground

00:11:23.470 --> 00:11:29.430
tests of a new kind of fission reactor that
could supply 1000 watts of electrical energy,

00:11:29.430 --> 00:11:36.610
and up to 10000 watts for installations on
the Moon, Mars or even for use in spacecraft.

00:11:36.610 --> 00:11:41.540
The reactor consists of an enriched uranium
core that’s undergoing fission decay.

00:11:41.540 --> 00:11:45.990
Heat pipes extend out from the reactor and
connect to Sterling engines which convert

00:11:45.990 --> 00:11:48.450
the heat into electrical energy.

00:11:48.450 --> 00:11:50.910
The whole system is self-regulating.

00:11:50.910 --> 00:11:54.970
If the reactor overheats, the engines can
draw off more power to cool it back down.

00:11:54.970 --> 00:12:00.360
If it’s too cool, the core contracts, increasing
the rate of fission again.

00:12:00.360 --> 00:12:04.480
With the ground tests complete this year,
NASA’s next step is to test them in space.

00:12:04.480 --> 00:12:09.040
If all goes well, future Moon or Mars explorers
will have all the power they’ll need to

00:12:09.040 --> 00:12:13.940
survive on other worlds, run their science
instruments, and transmit the results back

00:12:13.940 --> 00:12:15.820
home.

00:12:15.820 --> 00:12:20.470
NASA also thinks they could install these
kilopower reactors onto spacecraft that use

00:12:20.470 --> 00:12:26.760
ion engines, provide the electricity they
would need for extended missions.

00:12:26.760 --> 00:12:31.600
Solar panels, RTGs and fission reactors are
the three methods that space agencies have

00:12:31.600 --> 00:12:33.880
used to power their spacecraft.

00:12:33.880 --> 00:12:39.430
And who knows, as new technologies are perfect
down here on Earth like fusion reactors, maybe

00:12:39.430 --> 00:12:42.930
someday we’ll see those implemented in space
too.

00:12:42.930 --> 00:12:48.970
Until then, getting anything done, especially
anywhere far from the Sun is going to be incredibly

00:12:48.970 --> 00:12:50.950
difficult and slow.

00:12:50.950 --> 00:12:54.330
Like I said, space is the worst.

00:12:54.330 --> 00:12:56.820
Have you got any ideas for space-based power
systems?

